			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I know what I want isn't going to happen, and isn't likely to be balanced, but I figured I'd just put up some food for thought.
<br />

<br />
What I would like to see would be something to give us back a sense of uniqueness.  I've been told that we're pet-mongers, and even been called a "wizard with a pet", but I would wish I could do something no other class could do.  My personal favorite would be the "elemental game." (What I call it.)  Some of it is entirely codeable, I know.  Some of it would be rather intersting to see how it would code.
<br />

<br />
Basic rules for the Elemental Game:  earth and air oppose, fire and water oppose.  So we technically have 4 classes of spells, one for each element.  Air could have haste (pet or personal), Agility/Dexterity and AE spells.  Fire would be DD and Atk buffs (like the burnout line), Water could be Dots Stamina and HP buffs and heals, and Earth could be Str/AC buffs and snares/roots.
<br />

<br />
No pet can take a buff of its opposing element, nor could a pet have two opposing buffs on itself (So, say, an Earth pet could get the fire Atk buff, but would pay the price for by not being able to get the water's Stamina buff (I would make the heals far less effective, but not eliminate it).  Similarly, <span style="font-style: italic">if</span> the buffs were castable on others, they would likewise not be overwriteable.  The pets could also come with a single line of pet-specific proc-effects (air would stun, of course, fire is a DD, water would be a cold-based slow, and earth could be an AE root.
<br />

<br />
(BTW, I'd give mages a snare spell, but have it be short duration and break if the mob is attacked.  That way, mages would have a viable means of controlling and add or a few, without mimicing wizards and druids.)
<br />

<br />
Lastly, I'd give mages a line of elemental form spells, instead of the AA's.  The elemental forms would give a boost in the area the element specializes in, including the effectiveness of the spells of that line.  However, by taking on an elemental form, the magician gives up the ENTIRE LINE of spells of the opposing element for the duration of the form.  The AA's could then allow for specialization in a single element, making the spells of that element even more powerful, at the cost of reducing the oppsing element.
<br />

<br />
Basically the whole point of the "Elemental Game" is that magicians would have the versatility the elements would provide, but they would have to play a game of give-and-take.  How it would play out would be interesting, but would also stay reasonably in the realm of "you don't get something for nothing."
<br />

<br />
Like I said, just a thought for things I would think of that played off the "master of the Elements" theme.  I know it's not really doable, but just some thoughts to contribute to the pool.  Maybe someone out there can use it to come up with better suggestions.<br />_________________<br />Learn as if you will Live forever.
<br />
Live as if you will Die tomorrow.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
